<div id="review_2942072853" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2942072853" />
    <a title="Chris Dietzel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19351209-chris-dietzel"><img alt="Chris Dietzel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501356106p2/19351209.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2942072853?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris Dietzel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris Dietzel" href="/user/show/19351209-chris-dietzel">Chris Dietzel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2942072853" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10128677496080832657">I&apos;ve wanted to read this for a while because it&apos;s unanimously noted by the hand full of journalists I hold in high esteem as being hugely impactful to them. After reading it, I can see why, and I have a renewed appreciation for the very few people who report unbiased news. I&apos;m familiar with just about all of the basic concepts Herman and Chomsky discuss in the book but I&apos;ve never read such a thorough analysis of the ways the U.S. media distorts, misrepresents, or just plain ignores events to fit</span>
  <span id="freeText10128677496080832657" style="display:none">I've wanted to read this for a while because it's unanimously noted by the hand full of journalists I hold in high esteem as being hugely impactful to them. After reading it, I can see why, and I have a renewed appreciation for the very few people who report unbiased news. I'm familiar with just about all of the basic concepts Herman and Chomsky discuss in the book but I've never read such a thorough analysis of the ways the U.S. media distorts, misrepresents, or just plain ignores events to fit an establishment narrative. Although it was written in 1988, while reading it I noticed all of the exact same establishment news techniques being applied to the major story lines today. Like the book's tag line says, the U.S. media does not provide any kind of meaningful reporting necessary to understand world events. Those who have read it have left Plato's cave and see the world for what it is. <br /><br />Highest possible recommendation to everyone.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10128677496080832657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


